      "created_at": "2016-06-07 19:20:16 UTC",
      "updated_at": "2016-06-07 19:24:37 UTC",
      "body": "> Does YAML support multiple statements on the same line? Like a=1;b=2.\r\n\r\nYes.  It's not common style, but it is allowed.  The following are equivalent:\r\n\r\n```yaml\r\nfoo:\r\n  a: 1\r\n  b: 2\r\n\r\n# and this\r\n\r\nfoo: { a: 1, b: 2 }\r\n```\r\n\r\nBasically, commas and curly braces are inferred in the primary syntax (the upper example, which is whitespace-sensitive), just as semicolons are inferred in hocon.\r\n\r\nIf representing a list of values, a similarly json-like syntax is inferred:\r\n\r\n```yaml\r\nfoo:\r\n  - a \r\n  - b\r\n\r\n# and this\r\n\r\nfoo: [ a, b ]\r\n```\r\n\r\nBTW, YAML also has support for references, which is something that people have a tendency to forget about (since very few configuration formats support it).  For an example, see here: https://gist.github.com/bowsersenior/979804  Among other things, this allows YAML to natively support serialization of recursive data structures.  This is completely irrelevant for scalafmt, but it's still interesting."
    },
